In his State of the Union address, President Biden thanked the 118th Congress and congratulated the new Speaker of the House, Kevin McCarthy. He also acknowledged the new Leader of the House Democrats, Hakeem Jeffries, and the longest-serving Leader in the history of the United States Senate, Mitch McConnell. Biden highlighted the progress made in the economy, stating that 12 million new jobs have been created in the past two years. He also mentioned the advancements in the fight against COVID-19 and the resilience of American democracy. The President emphasized the need to rebuild the middle class and unite the country. He called for bipartisan cooperation and highlighted the importance of working together to address important issues such as infrastructure, healthcare, climate change, and immigration. Biden also discussed the need to address gun violence, protect women's reproductive rights, and support veterans and their families. He ended his speech by expressing optimism for the future of America and the strength of the nation.